[4] Viet Nam (Ho Chi Minh City)
Date: Fri 23 May 2008
Source: Thanh Nien News [edited]
<http://www.thanhniennews.com/healthy/?catid=8&newsid=38717>


More than 3000 children have dengue fever in Ho Chi Minh City, twice
the number last year [2007], the city's Health Department reported
Tuesday [20 May 2008].

Dr. Bich Lien, head of the Children Hospital 1's Dengue Fever
Department, said last week she was admitting 20-30 patients daily,
but that had gone up to 40-60 now.

Children Hospital 2 is treating around 60 children at the moment.

Mekong Delta provinces too have been hit hard by the disease, with
more than 10 000 cases having been reported so far this year [2008].

The Viet Nam Drug Administration last week instructed local health
agencies and drug firms to stock up on drugs to respond to the
current escalation of dengue fever.

--
Communicated by:
PRO/MBDS <promed-mbds@promedmail.org>

[More than 3000 cases of dengue fever in children have been reported
since the beginning of the year (2008), with reports of 40 to 60
patients being seen per day in the Children's Hospital in Ho Chi Minh
City. Almost 900 cases of dengue fever had been reported in Ca Mau,
Bac Lieu and Can Tho provinces in the Cuu Long (Mekong Delta) area in
the prior PRO/MBDS posting on dengue in Viet Nam.

More information from reliable sources on the current dengue
situation in the other regions of Viet Nam would be highly appreciated.

For maps of Viet Nam with provinces, see
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/middle_east_and_asia/vietnam_admin01.jpg> and
<http://www.angelfire.com/co/hongnam/vnmap.html>.

The HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Viet Nam can be accessed at
<http://healthmap.org/promed?v=14.9,108.5,5>.
This map shows other outbreaks in Viet Nam and surrounding countries
that have been reported on ProMED-mail. The postings can be directly
accessed through this map. - Mod.YMA]

[This same report was submitted by ProMED-mail Rapporteur Brent
Barrett. - Mod.TY]

******
[5] Hong Kong ex Maldives
Date: Tue 20 May 2008
Source: Health & Community News [edited]
<http://news.gov.hk/en/category/healthandcommunity/080520/html/080520en05006.htm>


The Centre for Health Protection today [20 May 2008] confirmed the
year's 12th imported dengue fever case involving a 39-year-old man
who traveled to the Maldives 5-13 Apr 2008. He was admitted to St
Teresa's Hospital on 28 Apr 2008 and has been discharged.

He came down with a fever, sore throat, joint pain and a rash on 22
Apr 2008. His 4 travel companions also had similar symptoms. Of them,
a 30-year-old man was confirmed to have dengue fever on 30 Apr 2008.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Brent Barrett

[New reports of continuing dengue transmission on the Maldives is of
concern. This is an additional imported case of dengue acquired in
the Maldives 3 weeks after the last reported case imported into Hong
Kong (see ProMED archive no. 20080505.1542). The Maldives had a
serious chikungunya epidemic in 2006 (see ProMED archive no.
20061224.3598), and it seems likely that there is a significant
population of _Aedes_ dengue virus vectors still there that could
support a serious dengue outbreak.

A map of the Maldives can be accessed at:
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/islands_oceans_poles/maldives_pol98.jpg>.
- Mod.TY]
